# Task Plan — [App Name] Clone

> Output of Phase 2a (Task Research) in `pipeline/build/ORCHESTRATOR_BRIEF.md`.
> Copy this file to `spec/TASK_PLAN.md` and fill it in. Do NOT ship
> TASK_PLAN.md with any `TODO` or `[fill]` placeholders — Phase 3 will not
> enter until this file passes the Phase 2 exit gate. Every claim here
> must be grounded in either `pipeline/qa/TASK-PROCESS.md` (for
> methodology) or `spec/FEATURES.md` + `spec/RESEARCH.md` (for app-specific
> pages, entities, seed records).

## Document contract (read before editing)

This file is one of four that must stay in sync. If you change one, update
the others in the same commit.

- `pipeline/build/ORCHESTRATOR_BRIEF.md` — the pipeline. Owns: phases,
  exit conditions, gates, subagent split. Reads: `FEATURES.md`,
  `RESEARCH.md`, this file.
- `spec/FEATURES.md` — the scope. Owns: feature inventory, Tier 1 vs
  Tier 2 split, failure-mode targets, seed data totals. Reads:
  `RESEARCH.md` (tokens), this file (task-driven seed records).
- `spec/RESEARCH.md` — the UI spec. Owns: screenshots, design tokens,
  per-page layout, interactive state matrix, testids.
- `spec/TASK_PLAN.md` (this file) — the task spec. Owns: failure-mode
  selection, per-task end-state, expected difficulty, seed-determinism
  mapping. Reads: `spec/FEATURES.md` (which entities exist),
  `pipeline/qa/TASK-PROCESS.md` (failure-mode table + per-task file
  structure + anti-patterns).

Agreement rules:
- Every failure mode tagged here must appear in the TASK-PROCESS.md § Phase 0
  table and in `spec/FEATURES.md` § "Failure-mode targets".
- Every entity referenced in a task row must appear in `spec/FEATURES.md`
  and in the Phase 2b System Plan entity list.
- Every seed record cited in a seed-determinism note must appear in the
  Phase 2b seed spec (so the seed subagent builds it without reading
  this file directly).

## 1. Failure-mode selection

Picked from `pipeline/qa/TASK-PROCESS.md` § Phase 0. Keep 3-5 primary
targets. Every task in § 3 must tag at least one of these.

| # | Failure mode | Fail rate (reference) | Why it fits {{APP_NAME}} |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | Mode confusion | ~80% | [one sentence citing a specific surface in Tab A — e.g. "Editing vs Suggesting vs Viewing toggle in the editor"] |
| 2 | Data-dependent reasoning | ~60% | [one sentence — e.g. "Find the doc with the most unresolved comments"] |
| 3 | Wrong visually-similar column | ~60% | [one sentence — e.g. "Home list view: 'Owner' vs 'Last opened by me'"] |
| 4 | Multi-step stateful workflow | ~50% | [one sentence] |
| 5 | Deep menu navigation | ~30% | [one sentence] |

Forbidden difficulty patterns (per TASK-PROCESS.md § "What does NOT work
as difficulty") — confirm NO task in § 3 relies on any of these:

- Single-workflow CRUD (navigate to one page, fill form, save)
- Reading and summing numbers from a list view
- Date-range filtering
- Creating calendar events or basic entities
- Generous tolerances (>10% numeric, loose text matching)

## 2. Seed-determinism discipline

Every task in § 3 must have ONE answer that is objectively correct given the
seed data. For each task, describe which seed records make the answer
unambiguous. The seed spec in Phase 2b will be derived from this column.

Rules:
- No ties. If the task asks "which X has the most Y," exactly one X has
  strictly more Y than every other.
- Both "has" and "has not" cases are seeded when the task requires
  distinguishing them.
- Answer values that are computed (sums, counts, averages) are queried
  from the DB by verify.py, not hardcoded.

## 3. Task matrix

Aim for ≥ 15 Tier-1 tasks. Each row: ID, one-sentence end-state, primary
failure mode from § 1, entities touched, expected difficulty per
TASK-PROCESS.md § "Task difficulty targets" (L1 easy / L2 medium /
L3 hard), and seed-determinism note.

| ID | End-state (one sentence) | Failure mode | Entities | Difficulty | Seed-determinism note |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| T01 | [e.g. "Resolve every unresolved comment on the Q2 Roadmap doc."] | Mode confusion | `documents`, `comments` | L2 | "Q2 Roadmap" doc has exactly 3 unresolved + 4 resolved comments; no other doc has 3 unresolved. |
| T02 | [e.g. "Share the Onboarding Handbook with emma.davis@x.com as Editor and set general access to Restricted."] | Multi-step stateful | `documents`, `permissions` | L2 | Onboarding Handbook exists; emma.davis is a seeded user not currently on the doc. |
| T03 | [e.g. "Find the doc shared with the most external editors and revoke every external Editor role on it."] | Data-dependent reasoning | `documents`, `permissions` | L3 | Exactly one doc has 4 external Editors; the next-most has 2. |
| T04 | ... | ... | ... | ... | ... |
| ... | ... | ... | ... | ... | ... |

## 4. Build order contract (non-negotiable)

Every task in § 3 will be built by a Phase 3 CUA-task subagent in this
exact order (per TASK-PROCESS.md § "Build order per task"):

1. `instruction.md` — conversational, no numbered steps, ASCII `--`.
2. `golden_apply.py` — programmatic correct answer via `POST /step`.
3. `verify.py` — SQL checks. Never written before golden_apply.py.
4. Smoke both directions: fresh DB → `verify.py` returns `0.0`;
   `golden_apply.py` → `verify.py` returns `1.0`.

Subagents build in batches of 5 tasks. After every batch they run both
smoke directions and fix verifier bugs before starting the next batch.
Phase 4.Tasks judging will check git-mtimes to enforce build order and
will reject any task where `verify.py` was written before `golden_apply.py`.

